<h2 id="interpret">Interpreting the Results</h2>
<p>
This service analyses the readability of all rendered content. Unfortunately, this will include navigation items, and other short items of content that do not make up the part of the page that is intended to be the subject of the readability test. These items are likely to skew the results. The difference will be minimal in situations where the copy content is much larger than the navigation items, but documents with little content but lots of navigation items will return results that aren't correct.
</p>
<p>
Philip Chalmers of <a href="http://www.benefit-from-it.com/">Benefit from IT</a> provided the following typical Fog Index scores, to help ascertain the readability of documents.
</p>
<table summary="Table containing some typical Fog Index Scores">
<caption>Typical Fog Index Scores</caption>
<thead>
<tr>
	<th>Fog Index</th>
	<th>Resources</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
	<td>6</td>
	<td><abbr title="Television">TV</abbr> guides, The Bible, Mark Twain</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td>8</td>
	<td>Reader's Digest</td>

</tr>
<tr>
	<td>8 - 10</td>
	<td>Most popular novels</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td>10</td>
	<td>Time, Newsweek</td>
</tr>

<tr>
	<td>11</td>
	<td>Wall Street Journal</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td>14</td>
	<td>The Times, The Guardian</td>
</tr>
